a secret British accent?","headlineShort":"Do you have a secret British accent?","image":["p05zf6kl"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":null,"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":["p05zf6kl"],"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fbritain"],"summaryLong":"Do you have a hidden Hugh Grant or Highland Scot inside? Take our quiz and we’ll pinpoint which part of the UK you most sound like you’re from – even if you’re not British.","summaryShort":"This quiz may reveal your hidden Hugh Grant or Highland Scot","tag":["tag\u002Fbritain","tag\u002Flanguage"],"creationDateTime":"2018-02-26T16:27:05.015556Z","entity":"article","guid":"a5329ce7-989c-44a3-98dd-ad3355f6194c","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180205-which-british-accent-is-closest-to-your-own","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:29:48.369406Z","project":"future","slug":"20180205-which-british-accent-is-closest-to-your-own","cacheLastUpdated":1587442990597},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much","_id":"5e982097272a584021aaf5cd","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"The British are famous for how frequently they say ‘sorry’ – even when they’re not at fault. But does the data hold up this stereotype? And is apologising so often really that bad?","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is probably the most over-used word in the United Kingdom: whether they are sorry about the weather or sorry because someone else has bumped into them, chances are your average Briton has blurted out at least one apology in the past hour or two.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA recent survey of more than 1,000 Brits found that that the average person says &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; around eight times per day &ndash; and that one in eight people apologise up to 20 times a day.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The readiness of the English to apologise for something they haven&rsquo;t done is remarkable, and it is matched by an unwillingness to apologise for what they have done,&rdquo; wrote Henry Hitchings in his aptly-titled Sorry!: The English and their Manners.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The average Brit says &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; around eight times per day","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut do the British really apologise more frequently than members of other cultures? If so, what&rsquo;s the reason for this peculiar verbal tic&hellip; and how bad a habit is it?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGetting reliable data on the frequency of apologies in different countries is harder than you might think. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s certainly speculation that Canadians and Brits apologise more than Americans, but it&rsquo;s difficult to study in a way that would provide any compelling evidence,&rdquo; says Karina Schumann, a psychologist at the University of Pittsburgh who studies apologies and forgiveness.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne approach is to ask people what they&rsquo;d do in a theoretical situation. For instance, a recent \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fyougov.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002F2015\u002F07\u002F01\u002Foh-sorry-do-british-people-apologise-too-much\u002F\"\u003EYouGov poll\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&nbsp;of more than 1,600 British people and 1,000 Americans revealed that there would be approximately 15 British &lsquo;sorries&rsquo; for every 10 American ones if they sneezed, if they corrected someone&rsquo;s mistake, or if someone crashed into them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"One recent poll found that there would be 15 British &lsquo;sorries&rsquo; for every 10 American ones","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut the survey found similarities between the British and American respondents, as well: just under three-quarters of people from either country would say sorry for interrupting someone. And 84% of Brits would apologise for being late to a meeting, compared to 74% of Americans.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDo as I say, not as I do\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, asking someone what they&rsquo;d do in a theoretical situation is very different to measuring what they&rsquo;d do in real life. Take the last example; in the YouGov survey, 36% of British respondents said they would apologise for someone else&rsquo;s clumsiness, compared to 24% of Americans.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut in her book Watching the English, social anthropologist Kate Fox describes experiments in which she deliberately bumped into hundreds of people in towns and cities across England. She also encouraged colleagues to do the same abroad, for comparison.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFox found that around 80% of English victims said &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; &ndash; even though the collisions were clearly Fox&rsquo;s fault. Often the apology was mumbled, and possibly people said it without even realising it, but compared to when tourists from other countries were bumped, the difference was marked. &ldquo;Only the Japanese seemed to have anything even approaching the English sorry-reflex,&rdquo; Fox writes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Only the Japanese seem to have anything even approaching the English sorry-reflex &ndash; Kate Fox","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe origins of the word &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; can be traced to the Old English &lsquo;sarig&rsquo; meaning &ldquo;distressed, grieved or full of sorrow&rdquo;, but of course, most British people use the word more casually. And herein lies another problem with studying cultural differences in languages. &ldquo;We use the word &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; in different ways,&rdquo; says Edwin Battistella, a linguistics expert from Southern Oregon University and author of Sorry About That: The Language of Public Apology. Brits might say sorry more often, but this doesn&rsquo;t necessarily mean they&rsquo;re more remorseful.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We can use it to express empathy &ndash; so I might say &lsquo;sorry about the rain&rsquo;,&rdquo; says Battistella. &ldquo;It might be that British and Canadian speakers use that kind of &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; more often, but they wouldn&rsquo;t be apologising, per se. Other researchers have talked about the use of &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; to communicate across social classes, where you&rsquo;re sort of apologising for your privilege.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBritish society values that its members show respect without imposing on someone else&rsquo;s personal space, and without drawing attention to oneself: characteristics that linguists refer to as &ldquo;negative-politeness&rdquo; or &ldquo;negative-face&rdquo;. America, on the other hand, is a positive-politeness society, characterised by friendliness and a desire to feel part of a group.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Brits might say sorry more often, but this doesn&rsquo;t necessarily mean they&rsquo;re more remorseful &ndash; Edwin Battistella","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs a consequence, Brits may sometimes use &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; in a way that can seem inappropriate to outsiders, including Americans. The British will say &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; to someone they don&rsquo;t know because they&rsquo;d like to ask for some information, or to sit down next to them &ndash; and because not saying &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; would constitute an even greater invasion of that stranger&rsquo;s privacy.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Our excessive, often inappropriate and sometimes downright misleading use of this word devalues it, and it makes things very confusing and difficult for foreigners unaccustomed to our ways,&rdquo; says Fox. Still, she adds, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t think saying sorry all the time is such a bad thing. It even makes sense in the context of a negative-politeness culture&hellip; Of all the words that a nation could choose to scatter about with such random profligacy, surely &rsquo;sorry&rsquo; is not the worst.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThere may be other benefits to saying &lsquo;sorry&rsquo;, too &ndash; such as fostering trust. Interestingly, that is true even when people are apologising not for mistakes they&rsquo;ve made, but rather for circumstances beyond their control.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn one study, Harvard Business School&rsquo;s Alison Wood Brooks and her colleagues recruited a male actor to approach 65 strangers at a US train station on a rainy day and ask to borrow their telephone. In half the cases, the stranger preceded his request with: &ldquo;Sorry about the rain&rdquo;. When he did this, 47% of strangers gave him their mobile, compared to only 9% when he simply asked to borrow their phone. Further experiments confirmed \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.hbs.edu\u002Ffaculty\u002FPublication%20Files\u002FBrooks%20Dai%20Schweitzer%202013_d2f61dc9-ec1b-485d-a815-2cf25746de50.pdf\"\u003Eit was the apology about the weather that mattered\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, not the politeness of the opening sentence.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Benefits to saying &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; include fostering trust &ndash; even when people are apologising for circumstances beyond their control","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;By saying &lsquo;I&rsquo;m sorry about the rain&rsquo;, the superfluous apologiser acknowledges an unfortunate circumstance, takes the victim&rsquo;s perspective and expresses empathy for the negative circumstance &ndash; even though it is outside of his or her control,&rdquo; says Wood Brooks.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf course, the British aren&rsquo;t the only group known for being apologetic. Women are often presumed to be, too.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo test if this stereotype stood up to scrutiny, Schumann recruited a group of university students to keep a journal for 12 days. They listed every situation they encountered where they felt an apology was deserved and whether or not one had been given. She found that the women did say &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; more often than the men, but they also reported more offenses when they thought an apology was needed &ndash; both for when they were the victim and when they were the perpetrator. When this was taken into account, men and women proved equally likely to apologise for their transgressions. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not so much that men are unwilling to apologise; it&rsquo;s just that they&rsquo;re seeing fewer offenses that deserve an apology,&rdquo; Schumann says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA sign of weakness?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESo what about those circumstances when we are aware that we genuinely owe someone an apology? Is it better to swallow your pride and say you&rsquo;re sorry, or &ndash; as the legendary American actor John Wayne put it &ndash; is apologising a sign of weakness?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;People worry that an apology will serve as an admission of liability, rather than as an effort to empathise with the wronged party,&rdquo; says Wood Brooks. But she adds &ldquo;effective apologies address the recipients&rsquo; feelings &ndash; they don&rsquo;t prove a point. A good apology is unlikely to backfire, and is more likely to increase trust than not apologising at all.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs for how to do it, Battistella has the following advice: &ldquo;The right way to apologise is the way your mother taught you.&rdquo; Say you threw a stone at a sibling. &ldquo;She&rsquo;d have you go and look them in the eye in the eye and say: &lsquo;I&rsquo;m sorry I threw the stone at you and I won&rsquo;t do it again&rsquo;. It&rsquo;s important to name what you did wrong, to show yourself as being penitent in some way and to indicate what might be different in the future,&rdquo; Battistella says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJust how many times you&rsquo;ll need to repeat the apology may vary according to where you live. Wood Brooks and Harvard PhD student Grant Donnelly have collected preliminary data that suggests that, for a minor transgression, the optimal number is a single &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sorry&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;If the transgression is large, then making two apologies seems to be the magic number for conveying empathy, remorse and restoring trust and liking,&rdquo; Wood Brooks says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf course, if you&rsquo;re British, you may need to double that. &ldquo;A single &lsquo;sorry&rsquo; does not count as an apology: we have to repeat it and embellish it with a lot of adjectives,&rdquo; says Fox.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApologise for the rain while you&rsquo;re at it, too.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFollow BBC Future on\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fmobile.twitter.com\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fplus.google.com\u002F107828172298602173375\u002Fposts#107828172298602173375\u002Fposts\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGoogle+\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&nbsp;\u003Cem\u003Eand \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.linkedin.com\u002Fcompany\u002Fbbc-com\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELinkedIn\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Cem\u003EThis story is a part of BBC Britain &ndash; a series focused on exploring this extraordinary island, one story at a time. Readers outside of the UK can see every BBC Britain story by heading to the\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fbritain\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBritain homepage\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E; you also can see our latest stories by following us on\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCBritain\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&nbsp;\u003Cem\u003Eand\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fmobile.twitter.com\u002FBBC_Britain\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much-16"}],"collection":null,"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2016-02-24T15:50:25Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"Why do the British say ‘sorry’ so much?","headlineShort":"Why do the British say ‘sorry’ so much?","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":null,"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":[],"relatedStories":[],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"The British are famous for how frequently they say ‘sorry’ – even when they’re not at fault. But does the data hold up this stereotype? And is apologising so often really that bad?","summaryShort":"Apologising frequently may have hidden benefits","tag":[],"creationDateTime":"2016-02-24T02:11:09.819412Z","entity":"article","guid":"d991a58b-b992-4a0e-88ee-b1391c23b22e","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:29:48.369406Z","project":"future","slug":"20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much","cacheLastUpdated":1587442990596},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common","_id":"5e982095272a584021aaeecc","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"The cut-glass accent of the aristocracy is losing some of its polish – a change that reflects some fundamental changes in British society.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIf the Queen&rsquo;s governess were still alive today, she may have noticed a few discordant notes in her charge&rsquo;s formerly crystal clear diction. OK, she ain&rsquo; exactly droppin&rsquo; her Ts and her Gs like Russell Brand, but linguists have nevertheless found that her enunciation today might have been considered a little, well, common in her youth.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer Majesty is by no means alone in this. The cut-glass accent of the upper class &ndash; the soundtrack to period dramas like Downton Abbey and Upstairs, Downstairs &ndash; has become a little rough around the edges over the last few decades, as more and more people adopt a kind of aristo-cockney hybrid.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDecrying the fall of the aristocratic accent may seem like a symptom of the peculiarly British obsession with class, but the fact that even the Queen no longer speaks the &ldquo;Queen&rsquo;s English&rdquo; of days gone by offers us a fascinating insight into the forces that shape our voices.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe idea of a &ldquo;proper&rdquo; accent only emerged fairly recently in the history of the English language. As Jonnie Robinson, a sociolinguist at the British Library points out, Samuel Johnson chose not to suggest the pronunciation of words in his Dictionary of the English Language, as he felt there was \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bl.uk\u002Flearning\u002Flanglit\u002Fsounds\u002Fcase-studies\u002Freceived-pronunciation\u002F\"\u003Elittle agreement about the correct way to articulate his terms\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. &ldquo;If you go back to the 18th Century, even the gentry, the educated and wealthy would have spoken with something like a local voice,&rdquo; Robinson says. Doctor Johnson himself was famous for having a Lichfield accent.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"It is solely by their language that the upper classes nowadays are distinguished, since they are neither cleaner, richer, nor better educated than anybody else &ndash; Nancy Mitford","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt was the increasing popularity of boarding schools that began to change the way the elite spoke, Robinson says, as they began to promote an accent that more closely resembled the sounds of the South East of England (where many of the schools and universities were based). Soon, the accent itself became a marker of class and power, an association that only became exacerbated when the BBC adopted this so-called &ldquo;Received Pronunciation&rdquo; for its first broadcasts (you can watch an example below). &ldquo;It was a voice that everyone in the UK and across the world associated with authority,&rdquo; says Robinson.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E{\"youtube\":{ \"id\": \"6bn6Sk5_iJA\"}}\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy the middle of the 20th Century, the class system itself had become a little more fluid; now, accent was one of the few ways to mark out those who had inherited their wealth from those who had earned it. As the novelist, essayist (and aristocrat) Nancy Mitford ironically expressed in the book \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FNoblesse_Oblige_%28book%29\"\u003ENoblesse Oblige\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: &ldquo;It is solely by their language that the upper classes nowadays are distinguished &ndash; since they are neither cleaner, richer, nor better-educated than anybody else.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPerhaps it was only a matter of time before that linguistic divide would begin to close too. As more and more people of working class background have begun to occupy positions of power &ndash; some characteristics of more regional southern English accents have started to creep into the crystal tones of Received Pronunciation. &ldquo;There are now those who speak a more modern form that verges on &lsquo;estuary&rsquo; English, which is a mixture of RP and cockney,&rdquo; says Jonathan Harrington at the Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the past, for instance, RP speakers may have said &ldquo;poor&rdquo; and &ldquo;moor&rdquo; with a diphthong &ndash; a combination of two vowel sounds &ndash; so that it sounds something like &ldquo;poo-uh&rdquo;; today, they are more likely to pronounce the words so that they sound identical to &ldquo;paw&rdquo; and &ldquo;maw&rdquo;. Conversely, the Ys at the end of words like &ldquo;really&rdquo; and &ldquo;very&rdquo; have become longer, and less clipped than in the past (when they sounded closer to the E in &ldquo;pet&rdquo;). Similarly, the As in &ldquo;the cat sat on the mat&rdquo; were once produced with a smaller mouth opening on the vowel, so it was pronounced something like &ldquo;the ket set on the met&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome younger speakers may even use glottal stops in place of the Ts in phrases such as &ldquo;it is&rdquo; or &ldquo;that is&rdquo;, Robinson says. To Mitford&rsquo;s ears, these changes would have sounded like \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FPygmalion_%28play%29\"\u003EPygmalion\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in reverse, as if Professor Higgins had taken the season&rsquo;s debutantes and turned them into cockney flower girls.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Kate speaks a little more conservatively than William &ndash; perhaps an ironic consequence of the snobbery surrounding her lowlier origins","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs a sign of just how prevalent this is, Robinson points out that even Princes William and Harry can be heard talking this contemporary RP that is verging on &ldquo;Estuary English&rdquo;. Indeed, at the time of the Royal Wedding, Robinson noticed that Kate (now the Duchess of Cambridge) spoke with a slightly more polished, conservative RP accent than her husband &ndash; perhaps an ironic consequence of the snobbery surrounding her lowlier origins, and her nerves at appearing on public display. &ldquo;If you move up a social set you have to try harder to use more prestigious forms,&rdquo; he says. If you watch the clip below you may see what he means.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E{\"youtube\":{ \"id\": \"Bn-eglpPKh8\"}}\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s not so surprising that younger people might adopt some of the tones they hear on the streets &ndash; perhaps as a reaction against their upbringing. &ldquo;There are these things we might do to seem cooler and trendier, but which we would drop when we get older,&rdquo; says Robinson.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou may not, however, expect to find the same traces in an 89-year-old monarch. Yet Harrington&rsquo;s studies have shown that even the Queen&rsquo;s accent has \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fscitation.aip.org\u002Fcontent\u002Fasa\u002Fjournal\u002Fjasa\u002F138\u002F3\u002F10.1121\u002F1.4933953\"\u003Esubtly shifted to a more standard, &ldquo;middle class&rdquo; Southern English accent over the decades\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Where she once said the word &ldquo;lost&rdquo; with the same vowel sound as &ldquo;law&rdquo;, it is now closer to the more common sound you may hear when Londoner Adele sings \"\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fyoutu.be\u002FBW9Fzwuf43c?t=50s\"\u003EI ain't lost, just wandering\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\"; family is no longer pronounced &ldquo;femileh&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJust listen and you might be able hear a subtle but noticeable difference. Compare, for instance, how she pronounces &ldquo;my own family often gather round (or, to approximate the way it sounds to my own working class ear, &ldquo;my own femileh awften gether rownd&rdquo;) in the first televised Christmas Broadcast of 1957&hellip;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E{\"youtube\":{ \"id\": \"KrtiD3nIHyQ?start=22&amp;end=33\"}}\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&hellip; with the way that she says &ldquo;I have been warned I may have Happy Birthday sung to me more than once or twice&rdquo; in the 2015 Christmas Broadcast.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E{\"youtube\":{ \"id\": \"8Mzor6Hf1tY?start=179&amp;end=190\"}}\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEven the simple phrase &ldquo;very, Happy Christmas&rdquo; at the end of the broadcasts reveals a shift with time. Here she is rounding off that 1957 broadcast:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E{\"youtube\":{ \"id\": \"KrtiD3nIHyQ?start=49\"}}\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnd here is the way she finished it in 2015:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E{\"youtube\":{ \"id\": \"8Mzor6Hf1tY?start=415&amp;end=426\"}}\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHarrington is sceptical that the Queen took some kind of elocution lessons in a conscious effort to sound less upper class. His analyses of the Christmas Broadcasts suggest the vowels slid slowly, almost imperceptibly from year to year &ndash; whereas if she was deliberately trying to emulate her subjects, then you would expect to hear a more abrupt shift.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInstead, he thinks an \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.phonetik.uni-muenchen.de\u002F~jmh\u002Fpapers\u002Fharringtonsoundchange.pdf\"\u003Eanswer comes from some interesting recent psychological studies\u003C\u002Fa\u003E looking at the art of conversation. Various experiments have found that each time we speak to someone, our accent moves very slightly to match theirs, perhaps an unconscious effort to build rapport. There is also some evidence that it improves \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F21135202\"\u003Eyour comprehension of what they are saying\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Importantly, the effects lingered after the subjects had said their goodbyes. &ldquo;If you measure their speech you often find that they sound very slightly more like each other after the conversation than they did before,&rdquo; says Harrington.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"What&rsquo;s fascinating is that despite her prestige, the Queen seems to have been making the same unconscious gesture of solidarity that we all make","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EHarrington points out that at the start of the Queen&rsquo;s reign, she may not have come into contact with many commoners on a regular basis, but with the greater social mobility of the 60s and 70s, people with a less upper-class accent would have slowly entered positions of power. &ldquo;Think, for example, of the prime ministers. In the 1950s, they were from aristocratic backgrounds, then in the 60s and 70s you have prime ministers who aren&rsquo;t from that background at all &ndash; Harold Wilson, Edward Heath, and Margaret Thatcher.&rdquo; That&rsquo;s not to mention members of her staff &ndash; and eventually, her own children and grandchildren &ndash; who may have all brought different voices to her ears.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn fact, he thinks you can see that broadcasters such as David Attenborough have been subject to the same forces, when you look back \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.youtube.com\u002Fwatch?v=692fiaoJWy8\"\u003Eat his first documentaries\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. &ldquo;This spontaneous subtle imitation is one of the main drivers of sound change,&rdquo; says Harrington.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhat&rsquo;s fascinating is that this subtle mimicry had previously been observed among subjects in the laboratory, not a reigning monarch. Yet despite her prestige and wealth, the Queen is still making exactly the same tiny, unconscious gesture of solidarity that we all do, meaning that each conversation has left its imprint on her speech. In a single vowel, we can therefore find a trace of all the people she has met, a sign of the changing voice of 21st Century Britain.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDavid Robson is BBC Future&rsquo;s feature writer. He is \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fd_a_robson\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E@d_a_robson\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E on twitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 500,000+ Future fans by liking us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fplus.google.com\u002F107828172298602173375\u002Fposts\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGoogle+\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.linkedin.com\u002Fcompany\u002Fbbc-com\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELinkedIn\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E and \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Finstagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E. \u003Cem\u003EThis story is a part of BBC Britain &ndash; a series focused on exploring this extraordinary island, one story at a time. Readers outside of the UK can see every BBC Britain story by heading to the&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fbritain\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBritain homepage\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E; you also can see our latest stories by following us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCBritain\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;and&nbsp;\u003C\u