as-the-queen-become-frightfully-common","cacheLastUpdated":1587442990597},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents","_id":"5e982099272a584021ab0006","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002F20150122-melissa-hogenboom"],"bodyIntro":"Our accent says a lot about our identity, but can also make us prone to stereotypes. As a result, many people want to change theirs – but how hard is it, and does it ever help, asks Melissa Hogenboom.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn terms of accents, I&rsquo;m in a sort of no man&rsquo;s land. I moved to Scotland from the Netherlands as a child and was lucky to learn English young enough to lose any traces of a Dutch accent. As an adult, I&rsquo;ve lived in London for almost a decade. The Scots think I sound English, the English say I sound Scottish &ndash; and the Dutch, well, they think I just sound a bit strange.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou would think that one benefit of my upbringing would be an adeptness at moulding my accent at will. Not exactly. During my secondary school&rsquo;s production of An Ideal Husband by Oscar Wilde, I used what I thought was flawless Queen&rsquo;s English for my character. Years later a friend from school told me that not only did I sound awful &ndash; embarrassingly I was the only one who had enthusiastically adopted a fake accent for a role.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf course, you only need to watch Oscar-winning actors to note that accents can be changed at will. Meryl Streep&rsquo;s flawless English in her portrayal of Margaret Thatcher is but one example. (Ironic, perhaps, as Thatcher famously tweaked her own Lincolnshire voice to sound a bit posher.)\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180205-which-british-accent-is-closest-to-your-own\"\u003EDo you have a secret British accent? \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you\"\u003EWhat your accent says about you\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20170720-the-hidden-ways-your-language-betrays-your-character\"\u003EThe hidden ways your language betrays your character\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut for most of us, changing our accents can be tiring and unnatural. Our accent forms a part of our identity. To change it is to lose an aspect of ourselves. Over time many of us do find themselves making small &ndash; or large &ndash; changes. Why we do so gives us a window into the fundamental role our voices play in our social world.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0616p36"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBritish accents lend themselves to all sorts of preconceptions and biases, as I \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you\"\u003Erecently explored\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The UK has a rich bag of eclectic accents and each come with their own particular stereotypes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"&nbsp;Listeners can attribute all kinds of unrelated personal traits to a speaker","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn an accent-shifting study, one participant \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftheconversation.com\u002Fjamaica-inn-complaints-reveal-widespread-accent-prejudice-22065\"\u003Etold\u003C\u002Fa\u003E linguist Alexander Baratta of the University of Manchester: &ldquo;If you&rsquo;re a Glaswegian on Casualty, you&rsquo;re gonna be violent. If you&rsquo;re Scouse, you&rsquo;re gonna be a scumbag. If you&rsquo;re from Newcastle, you&rsquo;re gonna be thick.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the US, meanwhile, the iconic drawl of the deep South \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.google.co.uk\u002Fsearch?q=southern+drawl+accent+stereotype&amp;oq=southern+drawl+accent+stereotype&amp;aqs=chrome..69i57.5223j0j7&amp;sourceid=chrome&amp;ie=UTF-8\"\u003Eis said\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to sound uneducated and New Yorkers can be deemed rude. Unfortunately, these stereotypes extend beyond TV shows and plays into the real world. Studies show that individuals who speak &lsquo;standard English&rsquo; are rated as \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1111\u002Fijal.12139\u002Ffull\"\u003Emore competent\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, as being \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.journals.aiac.org.au\u002Findex.php\u002FIJALEL\u002Farticle\u002Fview\u002F1020\"\u003Ebetter communicators\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and are often preferred candidates in &ldquo;prestigious jobs&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter all, you can wear professional-looking clothes and behave in a way appropriate to your job, but as soon as you open your mouth, your accent betrays your upbringing. As the linguist Chi Luu explained on BBC Capital, research shows that we are quickly judged based on how we speak: &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1002\u002Fejsp.2420100113\u002Fabstract\"\u003EListeners can attribute all kinds of unrelated personal traits to a speaker\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&nbsp;&ndash; from height, physical attractiveness, social status, intelligence, education, good character, sociability,&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.researchgate.net\u002Fprofile\u002FBere_Mahoney\u002Fpublication\u002F245157274_Accents_of_GuiltEffects_of_Regional_Accent_Race_and_Crime_Type_on_Attributions_of_Guilt\u002Flinks\u002F00b7d52cbccbb5fd1d000000.pdf\"\u003Eeven criminality\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0616qjs"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs a result, some people purposely choose to change their accents. They may wish to sound more &lsquo;proper&rsquo; or just to dial it down a notch, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.independent.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fuk\u002Fpolitics\u002Fgeorge-osbornes-man-of-the-people-accent-ridiculed-8675419.html\"\u003Eas several UK politicians\u003C\u002Fa\u003E have been known to do &ndash; often to much ridicule. Ed Miliband for instance was accused of trying to sound more common, changing words like &ldquo;yes&rdquo; to &ldquo;yeah&rdquo; and &ldquo;going to&rdquo; to &ldquo;gonna&rdquo;. Hilary Clinton too has been accused of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.youtube.com\u002Fwatch?time_continue=15&amp;v=JefxVoePPKY\"\u003Eadopting\u003C\u002Fa\u003E different guises depending on her audience.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt also happens in non-English speaking countries. In Sicily politicians change their accent depending on the class of their listeners, and tweak it again when they are speaking to politicians from other parts of Italy, explains Sicilian voice scientist Rosario Signorello at Paris&rsquo;s Sorbonne Nouvelle University. Accents are like fashion. They depend on the social context of the time, he says, and some speakers adapt their vocal behaviour accordingly.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor others, changing your accent is not a choice. Baratta discovered that some trainee teachers were asked to tone down their thick accents. &ldquo;Ostensibly it&rsquo;s about being understood,&rdquo; says Baratta.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0616pvq"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut that was the politically correct explanation. When probing deeper, he noticed linguistic preferences came into play, with a push for teachers to sound more standardised. One teacher even \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Feducation-39028994\"\u003Esaid\u003C\u002Fa\u003E he changed his accent specifically to sound less like the &ldquo;village idiot&rdquo;. This, Baratta says, shows clear bias against regional accents. He calls it &ldquo;accentism&rdquo; and likens it to racism. &ldquo;The real world is about accent diversity, so if you&rsquo;re diluting how you speak it&rsquo;s not a real representation,&rdquo; he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"&nbsp;As infants, we are masters of mimicry, an ability that diminishes as we grow older","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, several women in academia \u003Ca href=\"find%20it%20necessary%20and%20productive%20to%20lose%20a%20stigmatised%20accent%20it&rsquo;s%20possible%20to%20do%20successfully\"\u003Ehave said\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that they felt a pressure &ldquo;neutralise&rdquo; their regional accents in order to be taken seriously, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.timeshighereducation.com\u002Fnews\u002Fstudents-with-regional-accents-ridiculed-and-silenced\"\u003Ecalling it\u003C\u002Fa\u003E the &ldquo;last acceptable form of discrimination&rdquo;. Then there&rsquo;s Guardian writer Stephen Moss, who \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fcommentisfree\u002F2014\u002Fjul\u002F09\u002Fwelsh-accent-accentism-rp\"\u003Elamented about\u003C\u002Fa\u003E getting rid of his Welsh lilt at university as a result of feeling pressure to fit in. Today this leaves him sounding &ldquo;superficially posh&rdquo;, with Welsh sounds occasionally creeping in.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor those who decide to change their accent, whatever the reason, it is not an easy skill to master. Our accents are formed from a very young age. As infants, we are masters of mimicry, an ability that diminishes as we grow older. &ldquo;This requires synchronised micro-millimetre and microsecond-accurate control of the lips, tongue, velum, jaws, and vocal cords in order to produce precisely the right sounds,&rdquo; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.jstor.org\u002Fstable\u002F10.1086\u002F667654%20.\"\u003Ewrites\u003C\u002Fa\u003E Peter Trudgill of the University of Agder in Norway. This also explains why it&rsquo;s so hard to flawlessly pronounce words in another language as adults.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0616qbm"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs a result, for every Meryl Streep there are those who get it wrong. This includes performers: Brad Pitt in the Devils Own \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.belfasttelegraph.co.uk\u002Fvideo-news\u002Fvideo-the-worst-irish-accents-in-film-history-brad-pitt-as-rory-devaney-in-the-devils-own-31073265.html\"\u003Ehorrified\u003C\u002Fa\u003E those from Ireland, as did Sean Connery in The Untouchables.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn real life, language tweaks can be taken too far. Thatcher took elocution lessons to sound more authoritative; her teacher taught her how to lower her voice and to speak more calmly. But she started lowering her voice too much &ndash; and unfortunately for her, when a person lowers their voice it is usually an indication that they are about to end their sentence. &ldquo;That resulted in her being interrupted often. She overshot what teachers told her to do,&rdquo; says Leemann, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.researchgate.net\u002Fpublication\u002F232799616_Why_is_Mrs_Thatcher_interrupted_so_often\"\u003Ea finding\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that came about when researchers looked into why Thatcher was so frequently interrupted.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Whether we like it or not, we absorb and imitate other people&nbsp;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EEven when someone excels at imitating consonants and vowels, there are more subtle features about the way we speak that are hard to mimic. Adrian Leemann of Lancaster University and colleagues \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedirect.com\u002Fscience\u002Farticle\u002Fpii\u002FS0167639315001107\"\u003Eshowed\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that rhythm is so deeply ingrained in our first language that it can be tricky to copy. When the Scots say &ldquo;Please pass the butter&rdquo; they miss out the &ldquo;t&rdquo;in the final word, replacing it with what&rsquo;s called a glottal stop, so it becomes &ldquo;bu-er&rdquo;, whereas Americans might say &ldquo;budder&rdquo;. These different pronunciations also come with their own rhythm. &ldquo;It turns out if people do try to imitate it, most people don&rsquo;t succeed,&rdquo; says Leemann. What&rsquo;s more, it&rsquo;s below the level of consciousness for most people, he adds. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere&rsquo;s also the people who aren&rsquo;t faking at all but whose accents change over time. You only need to listen to BBC Correspondent Alistair Cooke&rsquo;s long-running radio show \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fprogrammes\u002Fb00f6hbp\u002Fepisodes\u002Fplayer\"\u003ELetter from America\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to realise this. When he first moved to the US \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fprogrammes\u002Fb0089htt\"\u003Ehe spoke\u003C\u002Fa\u003E standard BBC English, but several decades later sounded \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fprogrammes\u002Fp00sylxq\"\u003Eslightly more\u003C\u002Fa\u003E American. Similarly, author Bill Bryson remarked how his accent transformation &ldquo;was just what happened... my&nbsp;wife is English and&nbsp;my&nbsp;kids all have English accents, and every&nbsp;voice&nbsp;I hear is English. I've never intentionally changed&nbsp;my&nbsp;accent at all.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0616p0z"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is dubbed &lsquo;assimilation&rsquo; &ndash; a bit like mimicking someone else&rsquo;s body language, but with words. I too can recall experiences during travels where my intonation became distinctly more Australian or American. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not that you want to do it, whether we like it or not, we absorb and imitate other people,&rdquo; explains Jonathan Harrington of the Ludwig-Maximilians University in Munich.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"&nbsp;Accents remain difficult to truly change","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs we listen to each other, the words we exchange are imprinted on our short-term memory. Prolonged exposure to a different way of speaking then can influence our own accent. Harrington even discovered that the Queen has been party to this when he analysed her voice over the decades. As BBC Future has written about before, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common\"\u003Eshe has subtly tweaked her Queen&rsquo;s English to sound less, well, queenly\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. It can happen in more bizarre cases too, like when English football manager Steve McLaren started \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.youtube.com\u002Fwatch?v=2ZnoP4sUV90\"\u003Esounding a little bit Dutch\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut even if you successfully change your accent, if it doesn&rsquo;t match with how other people perceive you, then there may be no point in changing it at all. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Farticle\u002F10.1007\u002FBF00973770\"\u003EOne study\u003C\u002Fa\u003E showed that Asian Americans were judged as less comprehensible than white Americans despite the fact that they spoke with the same standard US accent.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor many, though, that is a moot point as accents remain difficult to truly change &ndash; which also means that overcoming any accent-bias is not easy. Perhaps I should be thankful of my slightly strange-sounding tongue. At least it doesn&rsquo;t give too much away.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cem\u003EMelissa Hogenboom is BBC Future&rsquo;s staff writer. She is&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fmelissasuzanneh\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E@melissasuzanneh\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;on twitter.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 800,000+ Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, and Travel, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents-18"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fin-depth"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2018-03-19T12:33:19Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"How hard is it to fake an accent?","headlineShort":"The people who fake their accents","image":["p0617nd0"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e98213a272a584021b09c21"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":["future\u002Farticle\u002F20180205-which-british-accent-is-closest-to-your-own","future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much","future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common"],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Our accent says a lot about our identity, but can also make us prone to stereotypes. As a result, many people want to change theirs – but how hard is it, and does it ever help?","summaryShort":"It is more difficult than you might expect","tag":["tag\u002Fpsychology","tag\u002Flanguage"],"creationDateTime":"2018-03-19T13:13:01.5952Z","entity":"article","guid":"e0db0091-aa0e-40b0-b1d3-e1bb263db9e6","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:29:48.369406Z","project":"future","slug":"20180315-the-people-who-fake-their-accents","cacheLastUpdated":1587442990594},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you","_id":"5e982098272a584021aafd8b","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002F20150122-melissa-hogenboom"],"bodyIntro":"Accents can be subject to subtle forms of prejudice, but does that mean some are more appealing and trustworthy than others? BBC Future takes a look.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOn 14 November 1922 the BBC broadcast its first radio report to the nation. We can&rsquo;t listen to it because it was not recorded, but we know this: the broadcast was read in flawless received pronunciation (RP), commonly known as \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common\"\u003Ethe Queen&rsquo;s English\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. It is considered to be the language of elites, power and royalty.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor many years, the BBC would only allow RP accents to appear on its airwaves. That this accent became synonymous with the voice of a nation had clear connotations. RP was trusted, authoritarian and sincere. Fortunately, the BBC now allows all sorts of regional accents on its broadcasts &ndash; and even encourages it, aiming to both represent the diverse audience the BBC has and to draw new people in.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the BBC no longer broadcasts only in RP, it turns out that the bias that once existed for it is still ripe in society today. Our accents can provide a window into our social backgrounds &ndash; and our biases. Our partialities can be so strong that they even affect our perception of who is, or is not, trustworthy.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180205-which-british-accent-is-closest-to-your-own\"\u003EDo you have a secret British accent? \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fcapital\u002Fstory\u002F20170523-does-your-accent-make-you-sound-smarter\"\u003EDoes your accent make you sound smarter?\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common\"\u003EHas the Queen become frightfully common? \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHumans are very quick to judge a person based on accents, and are often unaware we do so. &ldquo;Accent can trigger social categorisation in a prompt, automatic, and occasionally unconscious manner,&rdquo; says Ze Wang of the University of Central Florida. We often can identify a person&rsquo;s accent as soon they say hello.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p060chcq"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOur trust for certain accent starts extremely young. There is evidence to show that affinity for language even starts before birth. We know for instance that \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1111\u002Fapa.12098\u002Fabstract\"\u003Ebabies prefer the language\u003C\u002Fa\u003E they heard most while in the womb. \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.pnas.org\u002Fcgi\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1073\u002Fpnas.1302159110\"\u003EIn one study\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, researchers repeatedly played a made-up word while women were pregnant. When the babies were born, brain scans showed that only babies who had heard this word responded to it. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy the time babies are several months old, they can differentiate between languages and dialects. Early on, babies start to have an affinity for others who speak their native language. In one 2007 Harvard University \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.pnas.org\u002Fcontent\u002F104\u002F30\u002F12577\"\u003Eexperiment\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, babies watched two people speak on a screen, one in a familiar tongue and one that was foreign. One on-screen speaker then offered the babies a toy &ndash; which magically popped up from behind the screen at the same time. The babies preferred the toy given by the person who spoke their native language and accent.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Right away in the first year of life babies are starting to show this social preference &ndash; moving towards someone who speaks in a way that&rsquo;s familiar to them,&rdquo; says the study&rsquo;s lead researcher Katherine Kinzler, now at Cornell University.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p060cj88"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ETo Kinzler, accents are under-studied. They tie us to our identity in a similar way that our gender and race does. For some children, accent can be a more powerful indicator of group identity than race, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fguilfordjournals.com\u002Fdoi\u002Fabs\u002F10.1521\u002Fsoco.2009.27.4.623\"\u003Eshe has found\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. When five-year-olds were shown pictures of either black or white children, they preferred those who were the same race. At this age, they don&rsquo;t have the motivation to control prejudice in the way adults do, says Kinzler.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Children trust native speakers better than they do foreign-accented speakers","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut when colour was pitted against accent, the children preferred those who shared their accent &ndash; even if they were of a different race.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis work reveals that in our early years, the accents we trust most are those which sound familiar. It makes sense that we trust somebody who speaks like us, says Kinzler; they are likely to know more information about your own community.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3478775\u002F\"\u003Eanother study\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, she found that children trust native speakers better than they do foreign-accented speakers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p060chsp"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs children grow up they become more attuned to the social status or stereotypes that have been glued on to various accents. RP English is said to sound posh and powerful, whereas people who speak Cockney English, the accent of working-class Londoners, often experience prejudice. The Birmingham accent fares even worse &ndash; which \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.diva-portal.org\u002Fsmash\u002Fget\u002Fdiva2:944765\u002FFULLTEXT02\"\u003Ecould be\u003C\u002Fa\u003E the result of TV shows which depicted its residents as &ldquo;slow, lazy and thick&rdquo;, researchers wrote. Indeed, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fyougov.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002F2014\u002F12\u002F09\u002Faccent-map2\u002F\"\u003Eone poll\u003C\u002Fa\u003E found the Birmingham accent least attractive but rated Irish as having the nicest twang.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E(\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180205-which-british-accent-is-closest-to-your-own\"\u003ETake our quiz on British accents to find out which part of Britain you speak most like &ndash; even if you aren&rsquo;t British\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.)\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Trust in accents can change over time depending on our social circles and daily relationships","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen it comes to trusting accents, there seem to be two things at play. First, an accent represents part of your identity. But as you get older this might clash with an accent you aspire to sound more like, say one that is deemed more prestigious, or less stuck-up. One 2013 \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.comresglobal.com\u002Fpolls\u002Fitv-tonight-regional-accents-survey\u002F\"\u003Epoll\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of more than 4,000 people found RP and Devon accents the most trustworthy, while the least trustworthy was deemed to be Liverpudlian (from Liverpool). The Cockney accent came a close second for untrustworthiness. These accents scored similarly when asked about intelligence.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese are snapshot results, though. In real life, trust in accents can change over time depending on our social circles and daily relationships. A study by Ilaria Torre of Plymouth University found that trust in an accent can change depending on first impressions and judgements. In her study, participants heard either a standard southern English accent or a lesser-trusted Liverpudlian accent. If a person who spoke in the &lsquo;trustworthy&rsquo;&rsquo; accent then went onto behave fairly &ndash; by returning a generous monetary investment, for example &ndash; then this first impression of trustworthiness increased.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p060cqvb"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIf, however, a person spoke with the &lsquo;trusted&rsquo; accent and they went on to behave in an untrustworthy manner, they were deemed even less trustworthy than the person who had both an &lsquo;untrustworthy&rsquo; accent \u003Cem\u003Eand\u003C\u002Fem\u003E behaviour. The study participants &ldquo;were punishing them, so to speak, for not living up to the participants&rsquo; expectations,&rdquo; says Torre. The opposite happened, too: those who were judged as untrustworthy but acted nicely were able to undo negative preconceptions. In other words, the &lsquo;untrustworthy&rsquo;-sounding Liverpudlians (apologies, any readers from Liverpool) were redeemed when they behaved in a desirable way.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Our accent biases can be reduced by contact with individuals we initially think sound suspicious","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThis reveals something Torre feels has been overlooked &ndash; our accent biases can be reduced by contact with individuals we initially think sound suspicious. &ldquo;By interacting with speakers of many different accents we might realise our biases are unfounded and our trustworthy perception of that accent can change as well,&rdquo; she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe media plays a role too. Upmarket grocer Marks &amp; Spencer \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftheconversation.com\u002Fjamaica-inn-complaints-reveal-widespread-accent-prejudice-22065\"\u003Efrequently\u003C\u002Fa\u003E has a soothing, RP voice-over on its adverts, for example, while the more budget brand Iceland often featured former popstar Kerry Katona, who grew up in Warrington, a town between Manchester and Liverpool &ndash; until she was kicked off their adverts because of an alleged drug problem.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p060cht6"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the UK, some school teachers even have been asked to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.research.manchester.ac.uk\u002Fportal\u002Fen\u002Fpublications\u002Faccent-and-linguistic-prejudice-within-british-teacher-training(04ef40aa-a1f9-4cb4-b6ac-7cf4cfcf494d).html\"\u003Emodify their accents\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to sound less regional. Of course, says the University of Manchester&rsquo;s Alexander Baratta, while some people find regional accents to sound less educated, others think they sound more in-touch, sincere and friendly and that posh accents are more cold or arrogant. (This may be one reason why the Queen has been \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common\"\u003Etoning down\u003C\u002Fa\u003E her RP voice throughout the decades.) \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpdfs.semanticscholar.org\u002F45fd\u002F3bb53423f178852abc1c56036491554e20fd.pdf\"\u003ESome studies\u003C\u002Fa\u003E have found that people from Yorkshire seem to sound more honest than Londoners, for instance.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"People often have negative bias toward non-standard accents","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAccent biases are common against foreign accents too. A study led by Ze Wang showed that US participants trusted British accents more than Indian accents. &ldquo;People often have negative bias toward non-standard accents, particularly those with disadvantaged and low-prestige minority groups,&rdquo; she says. For instance, she found that those with Mexican or Greek accents were perceived as less intelligent or professional than those who speak standard US English. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F21988389\"\u003EAnother study\u003C\u002Fa\u003E showed that our accents can even limit our professional opportunities. Regional German accents were seen as less desirable than standard German, despite the same being said. But in Switzerland people preferred their surgeon to have a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpdfs.semanticscholar.org\u002F45fd\u002F3bb53423f178852abc1c56036491554e20fd.pdf\"\u003Eregional accent than\u003C\u002Fa\u003E a &ldquo;standard&rdquo; German one, perhaps because Swiss German is the most commonly spoken dialect.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen it comes to trusting accents, we depend both on what we know and on what society has conditioned us to aspire to. But if we all took a moment to stop and really listen to each other, we might learn to love the eclectic and varied accents that make up our multicultural world&hellip; rather than basing our trust on implicit biases that we acquire even before birth.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cem\u003EMelissa Hogenboom is BBC Future&rsquo;s staff writer. She is&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fmelissasuzanneh\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E@melissasuzanneh\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;on twitter.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 800,000+ Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, and Travel, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you-18"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fin-depth"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2018-03-09T12:57:23Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"What does your accent say about you?","headlineShort":"Do you have a trustworthy accent?","image":["p060ch9f"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e98213a272a584021b09c21"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":["future\u002Farticle\u002F20180205-which-british-accent-is-closest-to-your-own","future\u002Farticle\u002F20160223-why-do-the-british-say-sorry-so-much","future\u002Farticle\u002F20160202-has-the-queen-become-frightfully-common"],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Accents can be subject to subtle forms of prejudice, but does that mean some are more appealing and trustworthy than others? BBC Future takes a look.","summaryShort":"Some are subject to subtle forms of prejudice","tag":["tag\u002Fpsychology","tag\u002Flanguage"],"creationDateTime":"2018-03-08T08:57:55.586047Z","entity":"article","guid":"ec4bde88-05c2-4af6-ac49-afbfa7627ae2","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:29:48.369406Z","project":"future","slug":"20180307-what-does-your-accent-say-about-you","cacheLastUpdated":1587442990596},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones","_id":"5e982097272a584021aaf96b","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":null,"bodyIntro":"Ever been irritated by someone bellowing into their mobile phone in a public place? BBC Radio 4’s Adam Rutherford and Hannah Fry investigate the causes.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWe&rsquo;ve all winced at least once at the deafening sound of a commuter loudly conversing with someone on a mobile phone. But why is shouting like this so common?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecently, Drs Adam Rutherford and Hannah Fry have been answering questions from listeners and the BBC Future audience for a new BBC Radio 4 series called \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fprogrammes\u002Fb071c3y7\u002Fepisodes\u002Fdownloads\"\u003EThe Curious Cases of Rutherford and Fry\u003C\u002Fa\u003E (listen to the programme at the bottom of the page).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne query came from Daniel Sarano of New Jersey, USA.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Many people seem to talk loudly without realising, but is there a reason? &nbsp;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I have no interest in hearing about other people&rsquo;s private lives,&rdquo; wrote Sarano, \"the whole idea would have seemed anathema to older generations. I think they would have considered it rude to talk loudly in public.\"\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany people seem to do it without realising, but is there a scientific reason for their loudness?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe answer begins by looking at an aspect of telephone design that pre-dates the mobile phone, called &ldquo;sidetone&rdquo; &ndash; a feature whereby a caller could hear their own voice in the phone&rsquo;s speaker when talking.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis reassures the user that they can be heard, leaving no reason to raise one&rsquo;s voice. Landlines have sidetones specifically to prevent bellowing in offices and indoor space. But did mobiles do away with them? As acoustic technologist Nick Zakarov notes, no, they didn&rsquo;t &ndash; there are international guidelines that suggest a recommended decibel level for sidetone in mobile phones.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut the problem with mobiles is that they are mobile, and a fixed volume of sidetone isn't always sufficient where background noise is very high.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"We have a natural tendency to raise our voice to match the noise levels around us &nbsp;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EPlus, there's also the Lombard effect to consider. This is our natural tendency to raise our voice to match the noise levels around us. We tend to try and match the loudest sound we can hear. A pneumatic drill on a building site, for example.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHence the phenomenon of overly audible mobile phone chats.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s worth pointing out, however, that this would not be the first time that our use of phones has challenged the idea of good manners. When phones were originally invented, they raised all sorts of questions for Victorians. Should one have a phone conversation when undressed? Was it proper to stand up when speaking to a woman on the phone?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt seems phones, then, are a technology that may always pose new etiquette conundrums.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETo hear more, listen to The \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECurious Cases of Rutherford and Fry\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cem\u003E episode, &ldquo;The Aural Voyeur&rdquo;:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Video","iFrameType":"","videoImageAlign":"centre","videoUrn":[],"id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EOr\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fprogrammes\u002Fb070ffbh\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Evisit Radio 4 to download the episode\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;and hear more in the series.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you have any scientific cases you would like the team to investigate please email:&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"mailto:curiouscases@bbc.co.uk\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Ecuriouscases@bbc.co.uk\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones-8"}],"collection":[],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2016-03-04T00:47:21Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"The reason people shout into their mobile phones","headlineShort":"Why people shout into mobile phones","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":null,"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":[],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Ever been irritated by someone bellowing into their mobile phone in a public place? BBC Radio 4’s Adam Rutherford and Hannah Fry investigate the causes.","summaryShort":"The real reason for the annoying trait","tag":[],"creationDateTime":"2016-03-04T11:31:52.953939Z","entity":"article","guid":"ed02e966-6460-4f6a-a3fe-268c9b940bfe","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones","modifiedDateTime":"2016-03-04T11:31:52.953939Z","project":"future","slug":"20160303-the-reason-people-shout-into-their-mobile-phones","cacheLastUpdated":1587442990598},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20130227-what-is-killing-smartphones":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20130227-what-is-killing-smartphones","_id":"5e982094272a584021aae87e","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"In the third of a five part series on the future of mobile phones, Roland Pease explores what drains a smartphone battery so quickly... and what can be done about it.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is the curse of the modern age. After a day spent text messaging, emailing and browsing the web, your smartphone is dead. So now, after brushing your teeth and letting the dog out, there is another task: plugging in your phone.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut it never used to be like this. Simple handsets used to keep on going for days on end. So what changed? And more importantly, what is the mobile industry doing about it?&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe big difference is of course the technology&nbsp; -we used to talk on 2G phones that ran on the old GSM networks. They could last for almost a week, partly because we asked so little of them.&nbsp; As \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20130221-smart-networks-for-smartphones\"\u003Edetailed in the previous article in this series\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, smartphones became powerful computers because they needed to be to make strong, wireless connections to the network. And when they make those connections we ask them to do data-intensive tasks like stream video.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEvery single step along the way involves information processing. That takes currents flowing around silicon chips; and currents running round silicon chips generate heat, wasting energy. PC and laptop users are constantly reminded about this by the whirr of the fans that keep their processors cool. We don't notice it on phones, because everything they do seems to happen so silently, so effortlessly. But when you look at the detail, energy drips way like water from a leaky tap. And it all adds up.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETake the work of Dr Angela Nicoara, senior research scientist at the Deutsche Telekom Innovation Center in Silicon Valley. She has become something of a digital dietician, counting the joules that go into feeding our smartphones' appetites. She recently laid out her findings in \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww2012.wwwconference.org\u002Fproceedings\u002Fproceedings\u002Fp41.pdf\"\u003Ea report she enticingly called Who Killed My Battery?\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a collaboration with the group of Professor Dan Boneh at Stanford University, she connected a state of the art electronic meter to the battery of a smartphone, which typically store around 15-20,000 joules of energy, and then tracked the power for every millisecond it performed one of the most common applications for our handhelds: browsing the web.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhat emerged when she broke down the actions millisecond by millisecond came as a surprise.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first was that just hitting the &ldquo;go&rdquo; button and getting the phone to contact the network used 12 joules, as the phone exchanged details with the local base station, agreed transmission settings and so on. That&rsquo;s before a single byte was downloaded. When that process begins, the real surprises come thick and fast.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt turns out that the design of the web page has a massive impact on the energy it takes to put it on your mobile screen. For example, the BBC News website, specifically designed for mobile users, took another 3 joules to download and process all the bits for a news story. For the worst performer of the websites she explored, Apple.com, it took another 34 joules &ndash; 11 times more than the BBC. Wikipedia came just behind.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECareless websites, she found, are at least contributors to killing her battery. For our PCs and laptops connected to the mains, these numbers don&rsquo;t matter. With the constraints of a mobile battery they are critical.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe difference between these websites was in the way that they were built. For example, interactive elements that are used to customise a site experience and often run in the background of a site were a big drain. A half of those 34 joules needed to see the Apple page were down to &nbsp;these functions, without them even being touched; on Wikipedia, they alone cost 10 joules.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother drain are the so-called CSS files that tell a browser how to layout the page. Again, on the Apple site, these required 12 joules to download and render onto the screen. Simple improvements reduce this by 5 joules.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach joule might seem a trivial amount, but like a slimmer on a diet lots of small savings soon add up &ndash; especially when some websites take eleven times as much energy to visit as others.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectronic warfare\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut website design is not the only drain on a phone&rsquo;s batteries. The way we access these websites &ndash; and in particular the settings our service providers use - also has a huge effect, according to Hari Balakrishnan, Fujitsu Professor of Computer Science at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurprisingly, it is the network that decides what power setting our handsets use. When we need to transmit, the network tells our handsets to power up to maximum.&nbsp; But the network&rsquo;s interests are different from ours. We would like to power down again as soon possible to save our battery.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut only a slender portion of an already crowded radio spectrum is assigned for these so-called control messages, says Dr Balakrishnan. Because of that, the network tries to minimise the number of control signals it sends, even if that leaves our handset powering away while doing nothing.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&ldquo;A classic example,&rdquo; says Dr Balakrishnan, &ldquo;is when you&rsquo;re running an application that wakes up every 20 or 30 seconds and sends one byte of information. That would, in many cases, keep your radio in the high-power, active mode all the time. But it doesn&rsquo;t have to. That kind of trivial workload should consume next to no energy, but ends up using huge amounts of energy because of the sub-optimal controls implemented by the networks.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELike Dr Nicoara, Dr Balakrishnan decided to test his suspicion by wiring his battery to a meter and watching the battery drain. The results showed that by letting the phone control its own settings, he could halve the power consumed by the wireless transmissions with minimal effect on the network performance (although he stresses the details change from device to device, and from network to network).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAgain, these might seem small improvements overall &ndash; but a network that can give our phones a few more hours of working battery life is highly likely to attract more customers these days.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf course, it wouldn't matter how long your phone was fired up to exchange bits with the base station, if it could do so with minimal energy. But it turns out the mobile industry has been fighting a war with its electronics for years because they are so inefficient.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpecifically, it is the purity of the radio wave that they use to connect to the base station that requires so much power.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith radio spectrum restricted (see the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20130221-smart-networks-for-smartphones\"\u003Etwo previous\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20130212-mobiles-signal-dawning-crisis\"\u003Earticles\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in this series) transmission frequencies are squeezed in close together, and any distortion in the signal would lead to catastrophic interference. And it turns out that the basic physics of the amplifiers that drive the antennae can only generate those pure waves when drawing a lot of electrical current.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen the 3G standards were introduced, manufacturers turned to a special design of amplifier first concocted back in the 1930s, because of the stringent demands of the networks. But even then, for every watt of transmitted radio power, there's more than another watt simply warming your handset to create this pure wave. Basically, simple physics is doubling the drain rate on your battery.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The industry is racing furiously to mitigate this problem,&rdquo; says Joel Dawson, Professor of Power Engineering at MIT, who has himself come forward with a smart fix that involves electronically compensating for this distortion, something that could apparently halve the losses. But how soon any of those fixes will make it to the market remains to be seen.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnergy harvest\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf course these aren&rsquo;t the only drains on a battery. Modern smartphones pack everything from small accelerometers to energy hungry global positioning systems. And then there is the display - the whole selling point of the smart phone is the interface that lets you access the world wherever you are. Until researchers can develop electronic-inks similar to these used in the Kindle e-book or other pixelated passive systems that refresh as fast as lit screens, simply viewing the phone comes at a substantial cost.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe obvious solution would be to pack in a bigger battery, but of all the components in your handset, the battery is the one that represents seriously mature technology. Most of the electrochemistry was laid down a hundred years ago and, as one battery manufacturer confessed to me, there's little they can do about. The introduction of the rechargeable lithium-ion battery in the 1990s was something of a step change. But since then &hellip; well, while virtually every other phone parameter doubles in a year or two, it takes a decade to double battery performance.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are ongoing efforts to improve battery technology (See: \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20120227-charging-tomorrows-smartphones\"\u003ECharging Tomorrow&rsquo;s smartphones\u003C\u002Fa\u003E) but there may also be another route: harvesting energy from the environment.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESolar power is long-established, and has been tried many times with mobile phones, but has failed largely because of inconvenience. As the front of phones is crowded out with buttons, photovoltaic cells have largely been put on the back &ndash; but that has required turning a phone upside down to keep the battery charged.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut the form of the modern smart phone, freeing up the top face, has changed all that. And one potential solution is on display at this week&rsquo;s Mobile World Congress in Barcelona this.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWYSIPS (&ldquo;What You See is the Photovoltaic Surface&rdquo;), as it is known, is a joke, according to Francis Robcis, sales director for the new product. &ldquo;Because you can&rsquo;t see it,&rdquo; he explains.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnd it needs to be like that, because WYSIPS has silicon solar cells embedded within the large smartphone display.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Go into the office, and most people will leave their phones lying around with the face up,&rdquo; says Robcis. So that when the set is idle, the tiny silicon strips (too small to see) are busy recharging the battery.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe challenge has been to integrate the photovoltaics into the display without dimming the image by more than 10 per cent &ndash; a reduction users should find acceptable. And to allow it to sit alongside the touchscreen function. If the system takes off, the future mobile screen could become a busy place.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe company hopes to have a pilot line producing screens by the end of the year, to prove the technology is viable.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPowering by sunlight, of course, is conventional, even if unfamiliar in mobile phones. At the University of Washington Seattle, ex-Intel researcher Joshua Smith is planning something much more radical: powering mobile phones - with gratifying circularity - by radio waves.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis lab, funded by tech giants Intel and Google, has already made great strides. &ldquo;The largest TV towers in the US put out around a megawatt of energy,&rdquo; Smith explains. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re able to operate our energy harvester as much as 30 km from one and get small but usable amounts of energy.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn essence, harvesting radio energy requires rewiring the phone antenna to extract not the signal but the power of the carrier wave. And it&rsquo;s not only powerful TV transmissions that you can tap into. Recently, Smith&rsquo;s lab has been able to harvest energy from mobile phone masts.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe quantities available are down in the microwatt range, so not enough to power voice transmissions. But enough energy can be accumulated, Smith says, to send short texts, or just to stretch the battery life.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;It would be enough to have perpetual standby. My favourite example is driving along in my car. My son is playing Angry Birds on the cell phone, and completely drains the battery. And then I get a flat tyre. It would be nice if I could send an emergency SMS using this ambient energy. And of course, compared to solar power, you could even do it at night.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll of which means that the daily ritual of recharging your phone could soon be a thing of the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you would like to comment on this article or anything else you have seen on Future, head over to our \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003EFacebook page\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E or message us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002F#%21\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20130227-what-is-killing-smartphones-0"}],"collection":[],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2014-11-18T09:16:36Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"What is killing smartphones?","headlineShort":"What is killing smartphones?","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":null,"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":[],"relatedStories":[],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"What drains a smartphone battery so quickly... and what can be done about it?","summaryShort":"And what is being done about it?","tag":[],"creationDateTime":"2014-11-18T09:16:36Z","entity":"article","guid":"d2d6f5b9-7af1-4deb-8602-db188bd4d257","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20130227-what-is-killing-smartphones","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:35:10.266973Z","project":"future","slug":"20130227-what-is-killing-smartphones","cacheLastUpdated":1587442990598},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today","_id":"5e982097272a584021aaf7e0","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"Our close relationship with technology has made it easy for our devices to creep us out","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"calloutBodyHtml":"\u003Cp\u003EThis article was inspired by a \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fprogrammes\u002Fb080t0p9\"\u003EBBC Radio 4 episode of Digital Human\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, which is available as a podcast from Monday 31 October. Aleks Krotoski leads an exploration of the ways our machines can haunt us, from video game players experiencing Game Transfer Phenomenon to smart homes going haywire. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E","calloutSubtitle":"Listen to more tales of spooky technology","calloutTitle":"Haunted devices","cardType":"CalloutBox","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt wasn&rsquo;t late that Thursday night when the lights in my house started dancing. I was home alone, just about to finish work and start making dinner, when the lights suddenly turned on. Then they flicked off and on again, cycling from red to green to a cold, harsh blue.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENow, I don&rsquo;t believe in ghosts. But I am particularly susceptible to a good ghost story. I have a terrible fear of the dark that is in stark contrast to my otherwise rational, empirical beliefs. And I can&rsquo;t help but feel the icy bolt of my autonomic nervous system kicking into action when I think I&rsquo;m being threatened by the supernatural.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI blame a misspent youth watching psychological thrillers about creatures terrorising sweet young things in their dreams. I also blame a step-brother who was almost as playfully sadistic as the monsters in the films. Not long after \u003Cem\u003ENightmare on Elm Street\u003C\u002Fem\u003E had come out on VHS, John used his new Walkman to record a bit of Freddy Krueger off the TV. He set up a timer on the tape player, slipped it under my bed with the volume on high, and waited for my 2am wake-up call from the demon himself. John never channeled the occult &ndash; to my knowledge &ndash; but he liberally applied technology to make it seem like he had.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI didn&rsquo;t sleep for a week. John was grounded for longer than that.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat same year, \u003Cem\u003EElectric Dreams\u003C\u002Fem\u003E arrived in cinemas. It featured a schlocky love triangle that pitted man against machine for the affections of the woman who lived upstairs. Apart from the magnificent title song that haunts me to this day, what I still find compelling about this otherwise forgettable movie is how much of a period piece it is: \u003Cem\u003EElectric Dreams\u003C\u002Fem\u003E tapped into the uncertainty people felt at the time about what it meant to invite computers into their homes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"John never channeled the occult but he liberally applied technology to make it seem like he had","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EPCs were the new, weird boxes that everyone was talking about but few people actually understood &ndash; and yet we installed them in our private and personal domestic spaces. We trusted our friends, our families and the man on the television that this new thing should be in our lives. No need to know how it works! It brought convenience and seamless living &ndash; as we&rsquo;re told today&rsquo;s devices do now.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut when computers do things we didn&rsquo;t expect it&rsquo;s only natural that we would ask why. &ldquo;That simple question is so revealing of so many of the problems we have in our relationship with technology,&rdquo; says Tobias Revel of \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fhauntedmachines.com\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHaunted Machines\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a project exploring stories of myths and magic around technology. &ldquo;We at once express our lack of technical understanding for how the thing works, but we also put agency and responsibility into the thing. We assume that the thing is somehow responsible for the misfortune you are now experiencing.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWe imply that they know what they&rsquo;re doing &ndash; that they have a preternatural life within them. In short, that they&rsquo;re possessed: there&rsquo;s a ghost in the machine. &ldquo;We expect inanimate objects to remain inanimate,&rdquo; says Revel. &ldquo;When they deny what we have mentally constructed as the bounds of that object, that&rsquo;s when things appear to be haunted.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWe aren&rsquo;t the first to let ourselves believe that artefacts can be taken over. In 10th century Japan, man-made things were thought to gain spirit once they had been used for 100 years. If the owners had mistreated them, the objects would malevolently haunt them. More recently, the telephone, radio and television entered common use as spiritualism was gaining ground and we wondered what else was being pulled into these boxes that extracted voices out of the air. Spirit guides would connect clients with Benjamin Franklin and Alexander Graham Bell, as well as hosts of relatives who&rsquo;d already gone to the great telephone exchange in the sky.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The root of the supernatural and haunting is that there&rsquo;s no apparent connection between cause and effect,&rdquo; says Revel. The ghostly images in our television sets as we struggled to tune them, and the computers that say &ldquo;no&rdquo; when we know they should say &ldquo;yes&rdquo; are tiny little curiosities that interrupt the way we expect the world to be.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt comes down to trust. If a person said one thing and did another, we&rsquo;d stop believing in them. And if the thing they did was spin their head around in a way that was contrary to the laws of physiology, we&rsquo;d say there was a haunting going on. If our machines say they&rsquo;re going to do one thing, but do another, we&rsquo;re likely to stop trusting them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut the machines are not under their own control &ndash; they don&rsquo;t have agency &ndash; so we really need to look more closely at who&rsquo;s possessing these objects. When televisions entered our homes, people were worried that they would watch us after we turned off the lights. Now, technology companies have created devices to do just that.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWe are increasingly inviting &ldquo;smart&rdquo; objects in without truly understanding what&rsquo;s in their - literal and figurative - black boxes. Because they&rsquo;re internet-enabled, they&rsquo;re ripe for possession. &ldquo;In our rush to put a chip in everything, we&rsquo;re putting them into a system that&rsquo;s frail and fragile, and that&rsquo;s proven to be abused by malevolent individuals,&rdquo; says Revel. As science fiction writer Arthur C Clarke put it, any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic. Revel offers a twist: &ldquo;Any sufficiently advanced hacking is indistinguishable from haunting.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"&nbsp;Any sufficiently advanced hacking is indistinguishable from haunting - Tobias Revel","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161027-how-smart-homes-have-become-the-haunted-houses-of-today-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;If a smart home starts to go wrong, that becomes very sinister and dangerous,&rdquo; he adds. We rely on them to survive.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe night my lights took on a life of their own I sat on the sofa, paralysed with fear. There was no one else in the house except for the cat and the dog. My husband had left a few hours earlier on a work trip. With Ben flying to Norway, my psychological backup was 35,000 feet up.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBen&rsquo;s job is to test the future before anyone else has to, so our home is populated by smart devices: a NEST fire alarm that senses smoke and converse with our phones, a robotic hoover that does the dirty work when we&rsquo;re out of the house, a computer on the wall that automatically turns on when the house&rsquo;s Skype account is called, several voice-activated machines that connect to the web, and lights that &hellip; wait a minute!\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMy phone pinged. &ldquo;How&rsquo;re the lights?&rdquo; Ben asked. I paused. They continued to flash and change hue. The realisation slowly dawned.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Disco Party here,&rdquo; I wrote.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;&ldquo;It works!&rdquo; he replied.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBen was manipulating the internet-enabled devices in our house, messing with my personal space from the sky. And with that, the sheet was pulled off the ghost in the machine.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 700,000+ Future fans by liking us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http